{"version":1,"kind":"Article","sha256":"9af3105741a8e6ed08225bf30ce890454b70ceb93a33802b0694e023e519c373","slug":"reproducible-research.testing.testing-guidance","location":"/reproducible-research/testing/testing-guidance.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"General guidance and good practice for testing","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"The Turing Way Community","given":"The Turing Way","family":"Community"},"name":"The Turing Way Community","id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true},"code":{"id":"MIT","url":"https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT","name":"MIT License","free":true,"osi":true}},"github":"https://github.com/the-turing-way/the-turing-way","copyright":"2019-2025","numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"edit_url":"https://github.com/the-turing-way/the-turing-way/blob/main/book/website/reproducible-research/testing/testing-guidance.md","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"testing-guidance.md","url":"/build/testing-guidance-9945f23106638f6a80ee94b94bd0fcaf.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There are several different kinds of testing which each have best practice specific to them (see ","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"jexSEZ39on"},{"type":"crossReference","kind":"heading","identifier":"rr-testing-types-of-testing","label":"rr-testing-types-of-testing","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Types of Testing","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"iYUqM8ZcVT"}],"template":"{name}","resolved":true,"html_id":"rr-testing-types-of-testing","remote":true,"url":"/reproducible-research/testing/testing-overview","dataUrl":"/reproducible-research.testing.testing-overview.json","key":"rPkWF7KbpZ"},{"type":"text","value":").\nNevertheless, there is some general guidance that applies to all of them, which will be outlined here.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"ZqGzXwI0b5"}],"key":"sBACpl1Hob"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Write Tests - Any Tests!","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"ko2EKCGQVp"}],"label":"rr-testing-write-tests","identifier":"rr-testing-write-tests","html_id":"rr-testing-write-tests","key":"Yyh0HeyTEs"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Starting the process of writing tests can be overwhelming, especially if you have a large code base. Further to that, as mentioned, there are many kinds of tests, and implementing all of them can seem like an impossible mountain to climb.\nThat is why the single most important piece of guidance in this chapter is as follows: ","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"fS29jF2dkn"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"write some tests","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"j7WPNZCrr4"}],"key":"ywphBDNbJ1"},{"type":"text","value":".\nTesting one tiny thing in a code that’s thousands of lines long is infinitely better than testing nothing in a code that’s thousands of lines long.\nYou may not be able to do everything, but doing ","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"KchzkRNTrd"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"something","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"om6zvSi8Xo"}],"key":"VXgwuYnDlo"},{"type":"text","value":" is valuable.","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"nKimtet5So"}],"key":"osdf0rHxSK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Make improvements where you can, and do your best to include tests with new code you write even if it’s not feasible to write tests for all the code that’s already written.","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"aieec21etE"}],"key":"EgbzdkFjvm"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Run the tests","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"hB8LhDAOIc"}],"identifier":"run-the-tests","label":"Run the tests","html_id":"run-the-tests","implicit":true,"key":"lDQL8kvnaI"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The second most important piece of advice in this chapter: run the tests.\nHaving a beautiful, perfect test suite is no use if you rarely run it.\nLeaving long gaps between test runs makes it more difficult to track down what has gone wrong when a test fails because, a lot of the code will have changed.\nAlso, if it has been weeks or months since tests have been run and they fail, it is difficult or impossible to know which results that have been obtained in the mean time are still valid, and which have to be thrown away as they could have been impacted by the bug.","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"cPIGRsdABg"}],"key":"GF1bvzLyJB"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It is best to automate your testing as far as possible.\nIf each test needs to be run individually then that boring painstaking process is likely to get neglected.\nThis can be done by making use of a testing framework (","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"OY78PnlKPv"},{"type":"crossReference","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"discussed later","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"TrKWrnpylY"}],"identifier":"rr-testing-use-a-testing-framework","label":"rr-testing-use-a-testing-framework","kind":"heading","template":"{name}","resolved":true,"html_id":"rr-testing-use-a-testing-framework","key":"jLHYcRxYGp"},{"type":"text","value":").\n","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"GrDqU7AlEH"},{"type":"link","url":"https://jenkins.io","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Jenkins","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"Ly546A46SS"}],"urlSource":"https://jenkins.io","key":"lGgM60yNo9"},{"type":"text","value":" is another good tool for this. Ideally set your tests up to run at regular intervals, possibly every night.","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"T2RG2oNWcU"}],"key":"LosAmHN663"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Consider setting up continuous integration (discussed in the continuous integration chapter) on your project. This will automatically run your tests each time you make a change to your code and, depending on the continuous integration software you use, will notify you if any of the tests fail.","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"ZxRcQXW1K1"}],"key":"oCyrMGNlqS"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Consider how long it takes your tests to run","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"key":"gJnvMlZR8U"}],"identifier":"consider-how-long-it-takes-your-tests-to-run","label":"Consider how long it takes your tests to run","html_id":"consider-how-long-it-takes-your-tests-to-run","implicit":true,"key":"Rrl00j1XXV"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Some tests, like ","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"MVCU00D6E8"},{"type":"link","kind":"ref","identifier":"rr-testing-unittest","label":"rr-testing-unittest","url":"/reproducible-research/testing/testing-unittest","internal":true,"dataUrl":"/reproducible-research.testing.testing-unittest.json","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Unit Testing","key":"Rj7DommwLQ"}],"key":"GI5MG91gBP"},{"type":"text","value":" only test a small piece of code and so typically are very fast.\nHowever other kinds of tests, such as ","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"o6CShUgEB8"},{"type":"link","kind":"ref","identifier":"rr-testing-systemtest","label":"rr-testing-systemtest","url":"/reproducible-research/testing/testing-systemtest","internal":true,"dataUrl":"/reproducible-research.testing.testing-systemtest.json","children":[{"type":"text","value":"System Testing","key":"eIsIiLJVZY"}],"key":"OPHbcPmO0H"},{"type":"text","value":" which test the entire code from end to end, may take a long time to run depending on the code.\nAs such it can be obstructive to run the entire test suite after each little bit of work.\nIn that case it is better to run lighter weight tests such as unit tests frequently, and longer tests only once per day overnight. It is also good to scale the number of each kind of tests you have in relation to how long they take to run.\nYou should have a lot of unit tests (or other types of tests that are fast) but much fewer tests which take a long time to run.","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"XCcFPQSLDp"}],"key":"qwAR0Jh3KW"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Document the tests and how to run them","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"key":"pVwB7RguHP"}],"identifier":"document-the-tests-and-how-to-run-them","label":"Document the tests and how to run them","html_id":"document-the-tests-and-how-to-run-them","implicit":true,"key":"werh3DZXww"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It is important to provide documentation that describes how to run the tests, both for yourself in case you come back to a project in the future, and for anyone else that may wish to build upon or reproduce your work.\nThis documentation should also cover subjects such as","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"Pme6JqmNuz"}],"key":"tZS7Bu0UXa"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Any resources, such as test dataset files that are required","position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"key":"dyriA5372x"}],"key":"wYivB4rxmF"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Any configuration/settings adjustments needed to run the tests","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"fa92kBzYSI"}],"key":"QpY2fQ0Xrn"},{"typ