agraph","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":96,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Code coverage is a measure of how much of your code is “covered” by tests.\nMore precisely it a measure of how much of your code is run when tests are conducted.\nSo for example, if you have an ","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"key":"x36PUoZprb"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"if","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"key":"IJRiVqnkUN"},{"type":"text","value":" statement but only test things where that if statement evaluates to “False” then none of the code in the if block will be run.\nAs a result your code coverage would be < 100%.\nCode coverage doesn’t include documentation like comments, so adding more documentation doesn’t affect your percentages.","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"key":"v1UmJWbxHG"}],"key":"CK37zjGWAu"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":98,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As discussed any tests are an improvement over no tests.\nNevertheless it is good to at least aspire to having your code coverage as high as feasible.","position":{"start":{"line":98,"column":1},"end":{"line":98,"column":1}},"key":"k0FLb7noZT"}],"key":"p2dKyJ28QT"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Most programming languages have tools either built into them, or that can be imported, or as part of testing frameworks, which automatically measure code coverage.\nThere’s a nice little ","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"key":"XNWahMJ8yg"},{"type":"link","url":"https://codecov.io/","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"bot","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"key":"K1UeO0RTLZ"}],"urlSource":"https://codecov.io/","key":"fhAHD3YxkO"},{"type":"text","value":" for measuring code coverage available too.","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"key":"MWej9QJjQP"}],"key":"wKU2i8KJcc"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":108,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Pitfall: The illusion of good coverage.","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"key":"HnEdfiTA8U"}],"key":"dYaZ9tNaYs"},{"type":"text","value":" In some instances, the same code can and probably should be tested in multiple ways.\nFor example, coverage can quickly increase on code that applies “sanity check” tests to its output (see also {ref}","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"key":"TjyFomZo15"},{"type":"text","value":"), but this doesn’t preclude the risk that the code is producing the broadly right answer for the wrong reasons.\nIn general, the best tests are those that isolate the smaller rather than larger chunks of coherent code, and so pick out individual steps of logic.\nTry to be guided by thinking about the possible things that might happen to a particular chunk of code in the execution of the whole, and test these individual cases.\nOften, this will result in the same code being tested multiple times - this is a good thing!","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"key":"EYn1XEdRV0"}],"key":"WlKRbijuMu"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Use test doubles/stubs/mocking where appropriate","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"mMtdGz2zbA"}],"label":"rr-testing-guidance-mocking","identifier":"rr-testing-guidance-mocking","html_id":"rr-testing-guidance-mocking","key":"AkDbG7bsTB"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If a test fails it should be constructed such that it is as easy to trace the source of the failure as possible.\nThis becomes problematic if a piece of code you want to test unavoidably depends on other things.\nFor example if a test for a piece of code that interacts with the web fails, that could be because the code has a bug ","position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":113,"column":1}},"key":"XiUuHxhqS3"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":113,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"or","position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":113,"column":1}},"key":"iLsqKcr8Fq"}],"key":"otafiCnyye"},{"type":"text","value":" because there is a problem with the internet connection.\nSimilarly if a test for a piece of code that uses an object fails it could be because there is a bug in the code being tested, or a problem with the object (which should be tested by its own, separate tests).\nThese dependencies should be eliminated from tests, if possible.\nThis can be done by using test replacements (test doubles) in the place of the real dependencies.\nTest doubles can be classified as follows:","position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":113,"column":1}},"key":"Yt0AaDHkgo"}],"key":"kh7MFylwr5"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":131,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":122,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A dummy object is passed around but never used, meaning its methods are never called.\nSuch an object can for example be used to fill the parameter list of a method.","position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":121,"column":1}},"key":"oG7hKkmDsW"}],"key":"WProsRydMU"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":123,"column":1},"end":{"line":124,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Fake objects have working implementations, but are usually simplified.\nFor example, they use an in memory database and not a real database.","position":{"start":{"line":123,"column":1},"end":{"line":123,"column":1}},"key":"LxqD3D6dxG"}],"key":"fPC72uK2Hp"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":125,"column":1},"end":{"line":127,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A stub is a partial implementation for an interface or class with the purpose of using an instance of this stub during testing.\nStubs usually don’t respond to anything outside what’s programmed in for the test.\nStubs may also record information about calls.","position":{"start":{"line":125,"column":1},"end":{"line":125,"column":1}},"key":"IyopUsrpFT"}],"key":"p2znQ5Nu5L"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":128,"column":1},"end":{"line":131,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A mock object is a dummy implementation for an interface or a class in which you define the output of certain method calls.\nMock objects are configured to perform a certain behaviour during a test.\nThey typically record the interaction with the system and tests can validate that.","position":{"start":{"line":128,"column":1},"end":{"line":128,"column":1}},"key":"nbjkZ0DdND"}],"key":"ukEVsnvsSh"}],"key":"fLCUyQngKM"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":132,"column":1},"end":{"line":132,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Test doubles can be passed to other objects which are tested.","position":{"start":{"line":132,"column":1},"end":{"line":132,"column":1}},"key":"mW9HSutmZA"}],"key":"m69No4O4sL"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":134,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"You can create mock objects manually (via code) or use a mock framework to simulate these classes. Mock frameworks allow you to create mock objects at runtime and define their behaviour. The classical example for a mock object is a data provider.\nIn production an implementation to connect to the real data source is used.\nBut for testing a mock object simulates the data source and ensures that the test conditions are always the same.","position":{"start":{"line":134,"column":1},"end":{"line":134,"column":1}},"key":"YvDfgFlbVS"}],"key":"KHVe7P08t6"}],"key":"gpjaZX0maB"}],"key":"Lxn3ptSXxi"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Code Testing","url":"/reproducible-research/testing","group":"The Turing Way"},"next":{"title":"Overview of Testing Types","url":"/reproducible-research/testing/testing-overview","group":"The Turing Way"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3000"}